@ChainLeftist @Loopifyyy You would have no real way of knowing. I've seen several places using identical looking hashes as os as signatures, and have avoided them personally, but it was a disaster os refused to prevent.

@ChainLeftist @Loopifyyy The phisher was able to get them to sign something that essentially gave them carte blanche to nfts in their wallet. The signatures opensea asked for conveying no information at all was a phishing disaster waiting to happen. Imagine if collabland went rogue and asked for os sigs

@ChainLeftist @Loopifyyy It was a phishing attack, but one signature was able to transfer multiple nfts. That's a vulnerability. The signature itself was also part of the vulnerability - the inability to see what you were ever signing. They are switching to typed data now as a result.

... It had no importance at all. It clearly does have importance.

@rantingme ahh right. In reality, the 5 seconds shouldn't be a thing. I just had to simulate some sort of delay otherwise you would never see the Skeleton. :P

@rantingme The way its made by default, it takes 5 seconds to respond to each content request, and as it only calls StateHasChanged after it has loaded each of them and there are 5, it takes 25 seconds.
Could call StateHasChanged after each, but with no arbitrary delay I find it unnecessary
